posts.name: Jose Laureano
posts.cooked: I want to see if 550s are fast enough for a roller intake, and if they aren’t, what motors are that are not that much heavier or larger than 550s?

posts.name: Ashli Sincere
posts.cooked: we used a single 550 with a 5:1 reduction planetary gearbox for our intake last year, worked great.

posts.name: Ryan Stockton
posts.cooked: The Everybot uses a Neo 550 on the intake with a 5:1 reduction.

posts.name: Jose Laureano
posts.cooked: I saw the release video and the intake spins pretty fast. Would a 4:1 reduction with 6 inch wheels be too fast?

posts.name: Lucien - 4795 Alum
posts.cooked: yep, baby neos are real fast. usually you wanna gear them down a little; between 3:1 and 12:1 is a good range depending on wheel size

Yes, that would be way too fast. An intake should ideally be a bit faster than the drivetrain, somewhere around the 1.25 to 2x range. Anything faster just reduces the torque on the intake and makes it much easier to stall.

posts.name: paulonis
posts.cooked: Be careful if using a NEO550 with a belt/pulley reduction and a flexible intake.  The small diameter shaft that is cantilevered with a press-on pinion pulley has been known to break.  Not saying there is no way to do this successfully, but using a planetary gearbox for reduction is a more robust approach.

posts.name: Jose Laureano
posts.cooked: I was planning to use a 57 Sport gearbox, but it only had 4:1 ratios and 12:1 ratios

posts.name: paulonis
posts.cooked: There is a reasonable chance that with either 4:1 or 12:1, you can come up with a NEO550 motor speed that works with wheels you have.  4:1 and 6 inch wheels is probably too fast.  In ball intake games, the objective is to make sure the surface speed of your intake wheels is greater than the top ground speed of your robot.  That way, as you drive at balls they get picked up rather than driven over.  In this game, unless you’ve cracked the code on full robot width high-speed ground pickup of cones, the approach speed of intake to game piece is likely to be much slower than that of recent games.  A 12:1 NEO550 reduction and 6 inch wheels could be a workable combo while keeping the motor speed in a good power band.

posts.name: L J Brackney
posts.cooked: Be mindful of the 550’s stall torque/current characteristics and set your Spark Max current limits in the lower 20s.  We were burning up 550s on our intake last year and when we lowered the current limits sufficiently to protect them, we no longer had the torque we needed to intake over the bumper.  We also used a 550 on our indexer last year and it was VERY fast.

posts.name: Andy Mundell
posts.cooked:
If you are worried about weight, a NEO 550 + gearbox often is the same as a NEO/Falcon + single gear/belt reduction. And the full size motors come with more power and reliability. Food for thought.

Neo 550s are definitely fast enough. Without appropriate gearing they are too fast.

posts.name: Thomas Gormley
posts.cooked:
I’ve had multiple bad experiences with the 550

For something like your intake I think its better to slap a full size neo on and not worry about a huge gearbox or the motor failing.

posts.name: Ryan Dognaux
posts.cooked: Alternatively, a 775 Redline makes a great intake motor if you just want to run 2 wires out on your intake. Tons of power in a small package.

posts.name: Skye Leake
posts.cooked: … also no can bus wires out there vs w/ a Falcon. A few teams learned the hard way on that one last year.

posts.name: coderkevin
posts.cooked: We like using 775s on our intakes, simpler wiring, current limiting with a Talon SRX, and we don’t really use encoders on our intake motors anyway.

posts.name: Korey Gaddy
posts.cooked: We used a neo 550 with a 12:1 ratio on it for the 2022 game last year and it was super effective. We always found that 12:1 is the most effective for an intake. We use a 3:1 and a 4:1 planetary on whatever motor. Started with 775s and last year with a Neo 550.

posts.name: Jose Laureano
posts.cooked:
EDIT:

So my school already has 550s, and we aren’t going to buy any more parts if they are not necessary, since we are a small school and our budget is somewhat limited. Thanks for all the recommendations though!
